WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: I.V.M.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:36.000
[Amit Varma]: was Article 231, also known as the War Guilt Clause. This required Germany to disarm,

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.960
[Amit Varma]: to give up some territory, and most importantly, to pay reparations to some of the winners of the

00:00:40.960 --> 00:00:46.160
[Amit Varma]: war for the damage it had caused. The total cost of these reparations was later estimated

00:00:46.160 --> 00:00:53.840
[Amit Varma]: to be 132 billion marks, which would come to 442 billion US dollars today. Germany at the time

00:00:53.840 --> 00:00:58.480
[Amit Varma]: simply didn't have that kind of money, and in desperation resorted to just printing money.

00:00:58.480 --> 00:01:03.360
[Amit Varma]: Now printing money can lead to inflation, which is basically a tax on the poor. Germany printed

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:09.200
[Amit Varma]: so much of it that it led to hyperinflation, which was equivalent to waging war on their own people.

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:15.280
[Amit Varma]: The unrest that this caused led to the rise of Nazism, Adolf Hitler coming to power in the 1930s,

00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:19.520
[Amit Varma]: and eventually to World War II. Talk of unintended consequences.

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:24.480
[Amit Varma]: Now this was not something that was unforeseen at the time. The economist John Maynard Keynes

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:29.200
[Amit Varma]: wrote a book called The Economic Consequences of the Peace, which pointed out the reasons why

00:01:29.200 --> 00:01:34.080
[Amit Varma]: Article 231 would not work. Beyond saying that Germany could not afford these reparations,

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:38.240
[Amit Varma]: it also pointed out the problem that policy makers of those times faced because they simply

00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:44.240
[Amit Varma]: did not know the national income of the various countries. Had a measure called the GDP existed

00:01:44.240 --> 00:01:49.360
[Amit Varma]: at the time, the other countries could have taken one look at Germany's GDP and known that

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:55.600
[Amit Varma]: the reparations they wanted it to pay were just not possible. But they didn't. The GDP as we know

00:01:55.600 --> 00:01:59.920
[Amit Varma]: it was later born at the time of World War II and Keynes again played a part, publishing a book in

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:06.720
[Amit Varma]: 1940 called How to Pay for the War. The title of the book reveals the impetus behind GDP calculation.

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:12.800
[Amit Varma]: But I have a larger question that intrigues me. Had the GDP existed as a measure in 1919,

00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:20.320
[Amit Varma]: could we have avoided World War II? Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen,

00:02:20.320 --> 00:02:25.600
