00:51:03.360 --> 00:51:06.800
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Scene and The Unseen. I'm chatting with the economist Rajeshwari

00:51:06.800 --> 00:51:12.240
[Amit Varma]: Sengupta on the GDP and we spent the show so far talking about what the history of the GDP is,

00:51:12.240 --> 00:51:16.640
[Amit Varma]: how it evolved, the philosophical issues around it, what it measures and what it does not measure.

00:51:17.680 --> 00:51:23.440
[Amit Varma]: And now I want to turn to A, how do you measure GDP? Gross domestic product, what is it? This

00:51:23.440 --> 00:51:28.160
[Amit Varma]: is technical stuff. How do you measure it? And B, after that, come to what are all these

00:51:28.160 --> 00:51:32.800
[Guest]: controversies in India all about? Okay, so a quick trivia before I go

00:51:32.800 --> 00:51:37.200
[Guest]: into the technical measure of GDP. So since we talked about the history, when Kuznets and others

00:51:37.200 --> 00:51:43.200
[Guest]: came up with the measure, it was called gross national product, GNP. The idea was that it's the

00:51:43.200 --> 00:51:50.080
[Guest]: total market value of all goods and services produced by the people of a country within a

00:51:50.080 --> 00:51:54.240
[Guest]: particular year. And the people of the country, that notion was important for gross national

00:51:54.240 --> 00:51:58.800
[Guest]: product. I mean, the people of the country could be in US, could be in Japan, but it would be

00:51:58.800 --> 00:52:07.440
[Guest]: included in the US GNP. And that continued till about 1990s GNP. Around 1990s, we had this notion

00:52:07.440 --> 00:52:14.000
[Guest]: of gross domestic product. And gross domestic product is the total market value of goods and

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:20.080
[Guest]: services produced in a country in a particular year. And sold in the country. Yeah, produced and

00:52:20.080 --> 00:52:24.400
[Guest]: sold in the country, doesn't matter whether it is just by the people of that country.

00:52:24.400 --> 00:52:29.440
[Guest]: So therefore, basically, it means that if an Indian is sitting in Dubai producing something,

00:52:29.440 --> 00:52:34.880
[Guest]: that will be counted in India's gross national product, but not a part of India's gross domestic

00:52:34.880 --> 00:52:39.920
[Guest]: product. But if there is a Japanese guy sitting in Tamil Nadu in an automobile factory producing

00:52:39.920 --> 00:52:44.480
[Guest]: something, that will be a part of India's gross domestic product. And the reason this became

00:52:44.480 --> 00:52:50.960
[Guest]: important in the 1990s is once we had globalization, a lot of companies basically got the

00:52:50.960 --> 00:52:57.840
[Guest]: license to set up subsidiaries in emerging markets and other countries. So it got delocalized. And

00:52:57.840 --> 00:53:03.200
[Guest]: once it got delocalized, it became important to measure the output produced just within the

00:53:03.200 --> 00:53:07.680
[Guest]: geographical boundaries of the country. And the interesting thing that it did was, when you went

00:53:07.680 --> 00:53:14.480
[Guest]: from GNP to GDP, the size of the emerging economies just went up. Because emerging economies

00:53:14.480 --> 00:53:19.280
[Guest]: were then at that point of time, post globalization, were the hosts of all the subsidiary

00:53:19.280 --> 00:53:25.280
[Guest]: companies, outsourced companies, etc. So their output actually went up because you changed the

00:53:25.280 --> 00:53:30.320
[Guest]: definition from GNP to GDP. And of course, the emerging economies have been growing at a

00:53:30.320 --> 00:53:36.160
[Guest]: phenomenal rate since then. And I think a lot of that has to do with the definition change. But of

00:53:36.160 --> 00:53:40.240
[Guest]: course, they themselves have been doing quite well. Now, in terms of how it's measured, as I

00:53:40.240 --> 00:53:47.760
[Guest]: said, you basically value the, you assign a market price, market value to the total goods and

00:53:47.760 --> 00:53:52.880
[Guest]: services produced in the country in a particular year. And there are three different ways of

00:53:52.880 --> 00:53:58.160
[Guest]: measuring it. So think of a good or a service going through different stages. So there is a

00:53:58.160 --> 00:54:04.480
[Guest]: production stage, there is a distribution stage, and there is a consumption stage. So exactly to

00:54:04.480 --> 00:54:09.920
[Guest]: mirror that, Kuznets came up with three different ways to measure. You have a production approach,

00:54:09.920 --> 00:54:14.560
[Guest]: expenditure approach, and an income approach. So in the production approach, what you're doing is

00:54:14.560 --> 00:54:20.400
[Guest]: you are just estimating what is called value added. It's just as simple as total output minus

00:54:20.400 --> 00:54:25.760
[Guest]: total cost, whatever the total revenue of the companies minus whatever the value of the inputs

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:31.440
[Guest]: used. That's the production approach. Then you have the expenditure approach, where you are just

00:54:31.440 --> 00:54:37.680
[Guest]: summing up different expenditure components, and the total that you get is the GDP. And in the

00:54:37.680 --> 00:54:42.640
[Guest]: different expenditure components, you have consumption expenditure, you have investment,

00:54:42.640 --> 00:54:47.920
[Guest]: you have government expenditure, you have exports, and you would subtract import because import is

00:54:47.920 --> 00:54:52.240
[Guest]: something that you're spending on goods and services of other countries. Now, this expenditure

00:54:52.240 --> 00:54:57.920
[Guest]: component is actually, again, closest to the Keynesian idea, because Keynes was all about

00:54:57.920 --> 00:55:03.440
[Guest]: boosting demand by increasing expenditure of the government. And that fits really well with this

00:55:03.440 --> 00:55:08.400
[Guest]: Keynesian idea of the expenditure approach. And the third approach is the income approach,

00:55:08.400 --> 00:55:13.520
[Guest]: where it's basically one is equivalent of the other, because if the companies are producing,

00:55:13.520 --> 00:55:18.640
[Guest]: and you and I are consumers, we are consuming, then we are also getting some income because we

00:55:18.640 --> 00:55:23.760
[Guest]: are the factors of production. So the labour, land, capital, these are the usual factors. So

00:55:23.760 --> 00:55:28.880
[Guest]: the factored incomes that are being paid in the process of the production, get calculated in the

00:55:28.880 --> 00:55:34.080
[Guest]: income approach. And the idea is that all of these three approaches will yield the same number.

00:55:34.080 --> 00:55:39.360
[Guest]: There are some discrepancies here and there. But that's the overarching idea of measuring GDP.

00:55:39.360 --> 00:55:43.600
[Guest]: And that's pretty much what is followed in every country. So that's, that's the main measure of

00:55:43.600 --> 00:55:48.160
[Amit Varma]: GDP, so to speak. It's complicated, because in India, especially is complicated because

00:55:48.160 --> 00:55:52.800
[Amit Varma]: of so many bad labour laws and industrial laws, we have a very large informal economy.

00:55:53.360 --> 00:55:59.200
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, those statistics are very hard to come by. So, you know, how do we get around that?

00:55:59.200 --> 00:56:06.640
[Guest]: That's actually a very good point. Because so around the 1930s and 40s, after the World War,

00:56:06.640 --> 00:56:10.800
[Guest]: the United Nations was developing what is called the System of National Accounts,

00:56:10.800 --> 00:56:18.720
[Guest]: called the SNA. And the guy who was instrumental in building the SNA was Richard Stone, who actually

00:56:18.720 --> 00:56:23.920
[Guest]: won the Nobel Prize for that. The SNA was the idea is that it's going to set international standards

00:56:23.920 --> 00:56:30.160
[Guest]: for national income accounting for all the countries. Now, at that point of time,

00:56:30.160 --> 00:56:34.560
[Guest]: because it was primarily done for the developed countries, there was not much of a problem in it.

00:56:34.560 --> 00:56:39.440
[Guest]: But gradually, when GDP got exported to the rest of the world as the main metric of economic

00:56:39.440 --> 00:56:44.400
[Guest]: performance, it was realised that emerging countries or developing countries do have a

00:56:44.400 --> 00:56:49.840
[Guest]: very big informal or unorganised sector. And how would you value the output of this sector?

00:56:49.840 --> 00:56:55.280
[Guest]: Now, there is no easy answer to that. And in fact, the SNA is not really a very helpful

00:56:55.280 --> 00:57:01.200
[Guest]: outline to understand what's to be done. And in fact, the size of the informal economy is massive.

00:57:01.200 --> 00:57:06.160
[Guest]: I mean, in some estimates, it's about 40 to 50% in emerging countries. Even in India,

00:57:06.160 --> 00:57:11.200
[Guest]: it's a very, very big portion. And we don't have a very good measure of the informal sector,

00:57:11.200 --> 00:57:17.520
[Guest]: which means that you end up excluding a big productive part of the economy from the official

00:57:17.520 --> 00:57:22.720
[Guest]: measure of the size of output. And that's just a shortcoming that we live with. Because if you're

00:57:22.720 --> 00:57:27.920
[Guest]: following the international guidelines, we have no guidance there. And we ourselves,

00:57:27.920 --> 00:57:33.200
[Guest]: we have some crude measures of doing surveys, of figuring out what the informal sector contribution

00:57:33.200 --> 00:57:38.880
[Guest]: is, but they are far from perfect. So that's a big gaping hole in the GDP calculation of

00:57:38.880 --> 00:57:44.080
[Guest]: emerging countries, that we can't estimate what is the informal sector. And if I may digress,

00:57:44.080 --> 00:57:50.160
[Guest]: I think one reason why when demonetization happened in the country, we could not estimate

00:57:50.160 --> 00:57:54.480
[Guest]: the negative effect of demonetization, because majority of the effect was going to be on the

00:57:54.480 --> 00:57:59.600
[Guest]: informal sector, which is the cash-based economy. But because we did not have a good measure of the

00:57:59.600 --> 00:58:05.200
[Guest]: informal sector output, we could not measure what was the shock of the informal sector. And therefore,

00:58:05.200 --> 00:58:08.800
[Guest]: today we think maybe demonetization did not have that much of an effect, because we just don't

00:58:08.800 --> 00:58:15.280
[Guest]: have a measure of it. So it's very costly, when you can't measure about 40-45% of the economy.

00:58:15.280 --> 00:58:19.200
[Guest]: And then you have a measure of the organized sector, so to speak, and you make such a big

00:58:19.200 --> 00:58:22.560
[Guest]: deal of it. But that's just the state of the things today.

00:58:22.560 --> 00:58:26.880
[Amit Varma]: In fact, that even answers the question of why is a metric like the GDP important? It's important

00:58:26.880 --> 00:58:33.120
[Amit Varma]: because then you have a sense of where the government is messing up and what it's doing right,

00:58:33.120 --> 00:58:37.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, even if you don't think of it as a tool of central control. And I've had many episodes

00:58:37.680 --> 00:58:41.360
[Amit Varma]: in the demonetization, and all my guests make pretty much the same point that it absolutely

00:58:41.360 --> 00:58:44.960
[Amit Varma]: devastated the informal sector, but it's not going to show in statistics anywhere.

00:58:44.960 --> 00:58:45.440
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:58:45.440 --> 00:58:52.160
[Amit Varma]: And that's kind of sad. So how has thinking towards the GDP evolved in India over the years?

00:58:52.160 --> 00:58:57.760
[Amit Varma]: Like, give me a sense of who measures it? Is there like a government agency whose responsibility it

00:58:57.760 --> 00:59:02.640
[Amit Varma]: is to measure it? How have they arrived at a methodology? Is there a consensus around the

00:59:02.640 --> 00:59:07.520
[Amit Varma]: methodology? How reliable is the kind of data which they get? Tell me a bit about all of those

00:59:07.520 --> 00:59:08.080
[Guest]: problems.

00:59:08.080 --> 00:59:14.240
[Guest]: So, we have actually a very rich history of national statistics in India. And the reason I

00:59:14.240 --> 00:59:18.720
[Guest]: mentioned SNA earlier is because I wanted to talk about it, that when the system of national

00:59:18.720 --> 00:59:24.880
[Guest]: accounts was developed by the UN, in the 1950s, Indian economists and statisticians actually

00:59:24.880 --> 00:59:30.800
[Guest]: played a very important role there. In fact, VKR V. Rao, who was actually the founding father of

00:59:30.800 --> 00:59:37.120
[Guest]: Delhi School of Economics, he was a part of the system of national accounts building. And he

00:59:37.120 --> 00:59:39.760
[Guest]: contributed his intellectual inputs to their SNA model.

00:59:39.760 --> 00:59:44.240
[Amit Varma]: In fact, brief digression, our mutual friend, Niranjan Raj Thaksher, told me recently that

00:59:44.240 --> 00:59:48.560
[Amit Varma]: Dadabhai Naoroji had tried to calculate the national income in 1870.

00:59:48.560 --> 00:59:54.320
[Guest]: See, there you go. So I think Indians, and of course, then later on, we have a professor of

00:59:54.320 --> 00:59:58.960
[Guest]: Mahalanobis, right? I mean, he's like the father of statistics, so to speak, in India. So we had

00:59:58.960 --> 01:00:04.800
[Guest]: a very, very rich history of good statistics and statisticians and economists in India.

01:00:04.800 --> 01:00:09.840
[Guest]: And in fact, VKR V. Rao, again, interesting tidbit, was offered a position at Harvard

01:00:09.840 --> 01:00:15.600
[Guest]: University at the same time when Kuznets was, and he did not take it, he instead came and

01:00:15.600 --> 01:00:21.280
[Guest]: built the Delhi School of Economics. So that's how rich our background is. So we had the potential

01:00:21.280 --> 01:00:25.760
[Guest]: to really be, you know, at the frontier of the GDP statistics, but we have actually gone exactly

01:00:25.760 --> 01:00:31.440
[Guest]: the opposite way. So what happened is, in the past, we had, we were following the system of

01:00:31.440 --> 01:00:37.520
[Guest]: national accounts off and on, and we had a very good bunch of statisticians. There's an organization

01:00:37.520 --> 01:00:43.680
[Guest]: called Central Statistics Office, or the CSO. For the longest part till 1990s, a lot of the

01:00:43.680 --> 01:00:49.040
[Guest]: statistical work was done out of ISI Calcutta. And that's where the National Sample Survey

01:00:49.040 --> 01:00:54.560
[Guest]: Organization, the NSSO, was also set up. So the CSO, the Central Statistics Office, is primarily

01:00:54.560 --> 01:01:01.440
[Guest]: responsible for calculating GDP in the country. The CSO collects data from multiple agencies,

01:01:01.440 --> 01:01:05.920
[Guest]: ministries, etc., and collates everything together. There is a model that they use,

01:01:05.920 --> 01:01:12.400
[Guest]: you put in all the numbers, and you get a GDP size, and the sectoral disaggregations, etc., etc.

01:01:12.400 --> 01:01:17.680
[Guest]: And that is what has been happening for a very, very long time. Now, what happened recently is

01:01:17.680 --> 01:01:27.200
[Guest]: that in 2015, the CSO released a new base year series. Now, after almost every five or six years,

01:01:27.200 --> 01:01:32.240
[Guest]: the base year of the GDP is revised, because you need to calculate GDP in the benchmark of one

01:01:32.240 --> 01:01:36.080
[Guest]: particular base year, because otherwise the prices are fluctuating, and you want to keep the prices

01:01:36.080 --> 01:01:41.600
[Guest]: constant for one particular year. So the CSO releases in 2015, a new base year series,

01:01:41.600 --> 01:01:48.160
[Guest]: but the base year is 2011-12. The earlier base year was 2004-05. Now, when the series was released

01:01:48.160 --> 01:01:56.560
[Guest]: in 2015, what happened was the growth rate of the economy jumped significantly for all the years

01:01:56.560 --> 01:02:03.120
[Guest]: where we have overlapping data available for the old series and the new series. Now, why was this

01:02:03.120 --> 01:02:07.760
[Guest]: surprising? Because when you do a base year revision, base year revision is a very regular

01:02:07.760 --> 01:02:12.400
[Guest]: thing. All countries do it, we have done it many times, and you should. So when you do a base year

01:02:12.400 --> 01:02:17.440
[Guest]: revision, typically the size of the economy may change because you're probably doing a better

01:02:17.440 --> 01:02:23.040
[Guest]: capture, but the growth rate never changes a lot. It's just the economy is just maybe getting bigger

01:02:23.040 --> 01:02:27.520
[Guest]: in size, you're using better data and better methods, because you're capturing better,

01:02:27.520 --> 01:02:31.520
[Guest]: you're getting a bigger size of the economy, but the growth rate doesn't change. What happened

01:02:31.520 --> 01:02:38.000
[Guest]: in 2015 was we got a phenomenally increasing growth rate, especially in one sector, which was

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:43.840
[Guest]: the manufacturing sector. In fact, in one year, it went from negative growth rate in the old series

01:02:43.840 --> 01:02:50.480
[Guest]: to almost 6 and 7% in the new series, which is a huge jump. And that happened consistently for

01:02:50.480 --> 01:02:55.200
[Guest]: all the three years for which we had data of the old and the new we could compare. After one point,

01:02:55.200 --> 01:02:58.720
[Guest]: of course, the old data got discontinued, we couldn't compare it with anything else,

01:02:58.720 --> 01:03:04.800
[Guest]: we just had the new data. But the seeds of suspicion were planted in the minds of whichever

01:03:04.800 --> 01:03:09.600
[Guest]: economist and statistician was looking at this series and wondering to themselves, what is going

01:03:09.600 --> 01:03:17.440
[Guest]: on? How can you have such a high growth rate? And at that time, by 2016, we also got a feel of the

01:03:17.440 --> 01:03:21.920
[Guest]: economy by looking at other things, you know, we were in the basically in a banking crisis,

01:03:21.920 --> 01:03:27.200
[Guest]: exports were not growing, investment had stagnated. Now in a country where investment

01:03:27.200 --> 01:03:32.560
[Guest]: has stagnated for a few years, the banking sector is in a non-performing asset crisis,

01:03:32.560 --> 01:03:40.160
[Guest]: exports are not growing, how can you have an economy growing at 7%, 7.5%? And these kind of

01:03:40.160 --> 01:03:46.400
[Guest]: disconnects, these kind of questions started getting raised a lot in the academic circles of

01:03:46.400 --> 01:03:53.360
[Guest]: people who knew about the GDP measurement. And it was constricted within a group of a few economists

01:03:53.360 --> 01:03:58.000
[Guest]: and statisticians who knew about the process. And there was a lot of debate back and forth

01:03:58.000 --> 01:04:04.640
[Guest]: in journals and media and etc, etc. And that's when it started becoming more and more doubtful,

01:04:04.640 --> 01:04:10.320
[Guest]: that there are some problems in the new series, and it's much more than what meets the eye. And

01:04:10.320 --> 01:04:17.040
[Guest]: because GDP is such a complicated construct, as I said, not many people understand it. In fact,

01:04:17.040 --> 01:04:21.840
[Guest]: Robert Solow back in the 70s had a quote that every quarter you have economists talking about

01:04:21.840 --> 01:04:25.600
[Guest]: the GDP, but very few of them really understand what they're talking about, which is true even

01:04:25.600 --> 01:04:31.760
[Guest]: today. So it became clear that there's something wrong in the GDP. And some people started writing

01:04:31.760 --> 01:04:37.040
[Guest]: about the technical details of it, the methodology and etc. But the debate just went out of hand,

01:04:37.040 --> 01:04:42.880
[Guest]: because the moment I think media and whatever it is politicians, they started getting a sniff of

01:04:42.880 --> 01:04:48.080
[Guest]: that, oh, things are not right. It just went completely out of control. It was no longer a

01:04:48.080 --> 01:04:53.120
[Guest]: debate restricted within 10 people understood the process, it became a debate involving many,

01:04:53.120 --> 01:04:57.840
[Guest]: many people who did not understand the process at all, they just knew something was wrong,

01:04:57.840 --> 01:05:04.400
[Guest]: the GDP did not pass what is called the smell test. And therefore we need to attack, we need to

01:05:04.400 --> 01:05:10.880
[Guest]: criticize. And from then on, I think it just completely took its own form and shape. And the

01:05:10.880 --> 01:05:18.400
[Guest]: cost of it was that very little was written about in public media. But exactly what is wrong,

01:05:18.400 --> 01:05:23.040
[Guest]: and what can be done about it, it got so politicized so fast, that the Central Statistics

01:05:23.040 --> 01:05:28.800
[Guest]: Office got very defensive. They started defending saying, whatever we have done is in keeping with

01:05:28.800 --> 01:05:34.480
[Guest]: the system of SNA that I was talking about SNA 2008. It's in keeping with international guidelines,

01:05:34.480 --> 01:05:38.720
[Guest]: everything is perfect. So it almost became like two camps, like there's a camp of people

01:05:38.720 --> 01:05:43.040
[Guest]: who's criticizing the series. And there's a camp of people who's defending saying everything is

01:05:43.040 --> 01:05:48.560
[Guest]: right. And is this camp partly driven by politics? I would think so. Because it also unfortunately,

01:05:48.560 --> 01:05:53.520
[Guest]: or fortunately, whatever it is coincided with the time when BJP government came to power in 2014.

01:05:53.520 --> 01:05:59.440
[Guest]: And right after that, the new series was released. And then the new series showed this government in

01:05:59.440 --> 01:06:04.400
[Guest]: really good light because the economy was growing at breakneck speed. So automatically got politicized

01:06:04.400 --> 01:06:10.800
[Guest]: with people thinking that is there a political motive, or what's going on. And the CSO increasingly

01:06:10.800 --> 01:06:15.120
[Guest]: started withdrawing from the debate. Other institutions which are more political started

01:06:15.120 --> 01:06:22.000
[Guest]: talking about GDP. And it just got a really noisy debate, so to speak. And I think what we forgot in

01:06:22.000 --> 01:06:28.400
[Guest]: the process is that state capacity in India is weak. And there are many, many sectors of India

01:06:28.400 --> 01:06:34.320
[Guest]: where things don't work. You take crime, you take anything, basically. Now in a country where the

01:06:34.320 --> 01:06:39.760
[Guest]: state capacity is inherently weak, why would we expect a very complicated number like GDP to be

01:06:39.760 --> 01:06:45.360
[Guest]: perfect? I mean, it's almost obvious that there will be problems, there will be measurement flaws,

01:06:45.360 --> 01:06:50.240
[Guest]: and maybe people are trying to do the best that they can. But there are issues. But if you blow

01:06:50.240 --> 01:06:56.800
[Guest]: it out of proportion saying, oh, no, it's not 7.5, but it's seven, then it really becomes problematic,

01:06:56.800 --> 01:06:58.560
[Amit Varma]: unless you really understand what you're talking about.

01:06:58.560 --> 01:07:03.280
[Amit Varma]: So I have a couple of questions here. One is the methodology and the data,

01:07:03.280 --> 01:07:10.560
[Amit Varma]: are the methodology and the data that is used to calculate the GDP, are they open and available to

01:07:10.560 --> 01:07:15.280
[Amit Varma]: all to kind of look at? And the second problem that strikes me thinking from a point of view

01:07:15.280 --> 01:07:21.200
[Amit Varma]: of incentives is that if a lot of this data is coming from government agencies, and if it is

01:07:21.200 --> 01:07:26.240
[Amit Varma]: obviously an incentive, I mean, the government is incentivized to make itself look good,

01:07:26.240 --> 01:07:31.840
[Amit Varma]: then how can this data be reliable? And are there independent ways of either verifying this data,

01:07:31.840 --> 01:07:35.360
[Amit Varma]: or using other proxies to get a sense of I mean, whether it causes a smell test?

01:07:35.360 --> 01:07:43.040
[Guest]: Yeah. So what happened in 2015 was that there were many changes done to the GDP series other than

01:07:43.040 --> 01:07:48.720
[Guest]: just a base year revision. For example, for the manufacturing sector, which underwent the biggest

01:07:48.720 --> 01:07:55.440
[Guest]: changes, the entire data set that was used in the earlier series was replaced with a new data set.

01:07:55.440 --> 01:08:00.480
[Guest]: And since I need to mention the name, otherwise, it'll be difficult. It's called MCA. It's the

01:08:00.480 --> 01:08:05.440
[Guest]: Ministry of Corporate Affairs data set, MCA21 data. So earlier, we were using Annual Survey

01:08:05.440 --> 01:08:10.320
[Guest]: of Industries, ASI, and now we started using MCA21 data. So it was a big change.

01:08:11.360 --> 01:08:16.320
[Guest]: Then there were many other methodological changes in the way GDP was estimated in the new series.

01:08:16.320 --> 01:08:19.920
[Guest]: Now, these data are not coming from the government agencies. For example,

01:08:19.920 --> 01:08:25.200
[Guest]: MCA21 is a database where companies voluntarily file their financial returns,

01:08:25.200 --> 01:08:29.760
[Guest]: and on the basis of the financial returns, you're computing the GDP of the manufacturing sector,

01:08:29.760 --> 01:08:35.520
[Guest]: or of the services sector, basically. So many methodological data related changes were introduced.

01:08:36.160 --> 01:08:42.080
[Guest]: And it's possible that some things went haywire in that. But unfortunately, we can't test it

01:08:42.080 --> 01:08:47.280
[Guest]: because it's not publicly available. So as a researcher today, I cannot access the MCA21

01:08:47.280 --> 01:08:53.520
[Guest]: database. So while I may suspect that there are some problems with it, I can't conclusively prove

01:08:53.520 --> 01:08:56.960
[Guest]: that yes, there are problems because I don't get access to the database.

01:08:56.960 --> 01:09:02.080
[Amit Varma]: Why don't you get access to the database? I mean, just using the same RTI principle,

01:09:02.960 --> 01:09:05.600
[Amit Varma]: should not all citizens have access to these databases?

01:09:05.600 --> 01:09:11.520
[Guest]: Yeah, if you file an RTI, so MCA21 data, let's say there are 11 lakh companies that register

01:09:11.520 --> 01:09:15.760
[Guest]: with the Ministry of Company Affairs in any given year. Out of 11 lakh companies,

01:09:15.760 --> 01:09:19.840
[Guest]: let's say six or seven lakh are filing returns. You basically need all their data.

01:09:19.840 --> 01:09:25.520
[Guest]: And the MCA does not provide it publicly. You can pay a very small fee and get the data for

01:09:25.520 --> 01:09:30.400
[Guest]: one company for one year. And it just becomes a mammoth exercise if you want to get the full

01:09:30.400 --> 01:09:35.920
[Guest]: data set. So unless the MCA decides to make it publicly available in a user-friendly manner,

01:09:35.920 --> 01:09:40.320
[Guest]: it is very difficult for us to get that data. And just getting the data itself is not the end

01:09:40.320 --> 01:09:46.240
[Guest]: of the story, because you also need details of the methodological changes that the CSO

01:09:46.240 --> 01:09:52.720
[Guest]: had brought about. We don't even know that. So when the CSO brought about all these changes,

01:09:52.720 --> 01:09:58.000
[Guest]: there is a document which kind of gives an idea, but it's very vague. And there's a lot of opacity

01:09:58.000 --> 01:10:03.040
[Guest]: about it, that what were the exact changes and other technical details. Now, if they had been

01:10:03.040 --> 01:10:07.520
[Guest]: transparent about it, that listen, these are the changes that we did. This is the current method,

01:10:07.520 --> 01:10:12.560
[Guest]: all the nitty-gritty and details of it. And here is the database that we used. Now you are free to

01:10:12.560 --> 01:10:18.240
[Guest]: do whatever tests you want to do. They did not do that. So there's a lot of guessing game that

01:10:18.240 --> 01:10:24.400
[Guest]: researchers had to do to figure out what's wrong. And that, I think, kind of got the CSO more on

01:10:24.400 --> 01:10:28.560
[Guest]: the back foot. They got more defensive. And there was no release of information coming from their

01:10:28.560 --> 01:10:33.920
[Guest]: side at all. So end of the day, there is this opacity. There is a big suspicion that things

01:10:33.920 --> 01:10:39.600
[Guest]: have gone wrong. And there is absolutely no response from the CSO admitting that, yeah,

01:10:39.600 --> 01:10:43.920
[Guest]: maybe there are some problems or you guys find it out for yourselves. We are making the documents

01:10:43.920 --> 01:10:49.440
[Guest]: transparent. And that ended up this camp thing that, you know, I mean, some people are just

01:10:49.440 --> 01:10:54.960
[Guest]: convinced that there are problems with the GDP data, the CSO. And now the government basically

01:10:54.960 --> 01:11:00.000
[Guest]: says that, no, no, everything is fine. And you're almost at an impasse because what do you do? And

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:05.200
[Guest]: what ended up happening, the negative effect of that is that I think people started losing the

01:11:05.200 --> 01:11:10.640
[Guest]: trust in GDP. When I talked to many of my financial market friends in Bombay, they tell me that

01:11:10.640 --> 01:11:16.640
[Guest]: routinely when the GDP number comes out, they always subtract 2% from that number. And they

01:11:16.640 --> 01:11:22.320
[Guest]: take that as the actual growth rate because they feel they can't trust the actual official number.

01:11:22.320 --> 01:11:27.680
[Guest]: There's no reliability of it. I often tell my own students that, you know, you can work on macro

01:11:27.680 --> 01:11:32.400
[Guest]: research, but you can't use the GDP data. Imagine what a handicap that is if you're studying the

01:11:32.400 --> 01:11:38.240
[Guest]: macroeconomic situation of the country, but you can't use GDP data. Also, what happened with this

01:11:38.240 --> 01:11:45.280
[Guest]: revision, we don't have a continuous series going backward. So we have a GDP data now from 2011-12,

01:11:45.280 --> 01:11:51.840
[Guest]: but nothing going back to the 1950s. So when you don't have a continuous series, how do you

01:11:51.840 --> 01:11:57.200
[Guest]: track the progress of the economy over time? So even that got affected. In fact, there was a,

01:11:57.200 --> 01:12:01.120
[Guest]: typically what happens when you do a base year revision, you're also supposed to release a back

01:12:01.120 --> 01:12:08.000
[Guest]: series to link it with the older one. And the CSO did that, except the back series showed that

01:12:08.000 --> 01:12:14.560
[Guest]: during the boom period, what you and I know as the boom period of 2004-2008, the Indian growth

01:12:14.560 --> 01:12:20.720
[Guest]: rate was lower than what it has been over the last five years. So you just change our perception of

01:12:20.720 --> 01:12:25.280
[Amit Varma]: history. And there is a smell test issue to that, quite frankly, because you know, just having

01:12:25.280 --> 01:12:29.680
[Amit Varma]: lived through that time and living through this time. Exactly. And I think with that release,

01:12:29.680 --> 01:12:34.800
[Guest]: they actually lost all credibility, because when you just tell the country that, oh, it was not the

01:12:34.800 --> 01:12:39.920
[Guest]: boom period that you thought it was, because we have changed things. And that also, they were

01:12:39.920 --> 01:12:44.640
[Guest]: really opaque about the back series method, how they did it. I mean, we tried to recreate it,

01:12:44.640 --> 01:12:49.760
[Guest]: and we could not because we just didn't have access to information. So all of these things,

01:12:49.760 --> 01:12:54.720
[Guest]: it just was no longer just a base year revision or just a methodological improvement in keeping

01:12:54.720 --> 01:13:00.240
[Guest]: with SNA. They started doing many, many things, which really affected the credibility of the

01:13:00.240 --> 01:13:06.080
[Guest]: statistical office itself. And when that started happening, you know, you just, as I said, you

01:13:06.080 --> 01:13:10.320
[Amit Varma]: don't trust the GDP number anymore. And, you know, typically, the first instinct would be that,

01:13:10.320 --> 01:13:14.160
[Amit Varma]: okay, they changed the methodology a little bit and all, maybe they did it in good faith,

01:13:14.160 --> 01:13:18.320
[Amit Varma]: and let's not bring politics into it and so on. But then when you say that they are not being

01:13:18.320 --> 01:13:23.120
[Amit Varma]: transparent about it, and they're just asking us to trust them blindly, then I think the default

01:13:23.120 --> 01:13:26.160
[Amit Varma]: mode has to be suspicion and to say that there is something fishy here.

01:13:26.160 --> 01:13:30.320
[Guest]: Exactly. Because when you see that there are so many people criticizing it, some of them

01:13:30.320 --> 01:13:34.480
[Guest]: know what they're talking about, some of them may not know, but still, all you had to do as the

01:13:34.480 --> 01:13:38.640
[Guest]: statistical agency of the country is just come out in the open and say, listen, guys, this is

01:13:38.640 --> 01:13:43.600
[Guest]: the details of what we have done. And yeah, maybe there are some problems here or there, maybe you

01:13:43.600 --> 01:13:48.320
[Guest]: should have had some caviar, take it with a pinch of salt. But this is in the interest of the

01:13:48.320 --> 01:13:51.920
[Guest]: economy, because we want to do a better capture, blah, blah, blah. But we are going to give you

01:13:51.920 --> 01:13:55.600
[Guest]: all the information, there is no reason for them to withhold information from us.

01:13:55.600 --> 01:13:57.680
[Guest]: I mean, they could literally crowdsource all the hard work.

01:13:57.680 --> 01:14:04.160
[Guest]: Absolutely, absolutely. And you know, the quest should be to improve GDP estimation method,

01:14:04.160 --> 01:14:08.400
[Guest]: and to involve more and more stakeholders. And it's extremely important, I think,

01:14:08.400 --> 01:14:14.240
[Guest]: when it's a national statistic number, you need to buy in the trust of the stakeholders. Otherwise,

01:14:14.240 --> 01:14:18.560
[Guest]: who are you really creating this number for? I mean, are you just creating the number in

01:14:18.560 --> 01:14:21.920
[Guest]: because you want to participate in a global rat race of being the fastest growing country when

01:14:21.920 --> 01:14:27.040
[Guest]: nobody in your country believes in the data? So what is it that the objective is? And especially

01:14:27.040 --> 01:14:33.680
[Guest]: when you are in a country with such a rich history and heritage of statistics, then why would you do

01:14:33.680 --> 01:14:37.680
[Guest]: something like that? Why can't you just be transparent and say, this is all that there is,

01:14:37.680 --> 01:14:42.160
[Guest]: and you guys figure out if you really have the expertise. And I personally have not just been

01:14:42.160 --> 01:14:46.160
[Guest]: able to understand what is the resistance and what what's the reason behind this opacity.

01:14:46.160 --> 01:14:50.320
[Guest]: And if there is so much of a criticism, instead of being defensive and saying,

01:14:50.320 --> 01:14:54.800
[Guest]: no, no, it's an attack, and blah, blah, blah, everything is well, and doing more stuff like

01:14:54.800 --> 01:14:59.280
[Guest]: releasing a back series, which says the boom period was not a boom period. Why would you do

01:14:59.280 --> 01:15:02.960
[Guest]: something like that? Right? I mean, unless you were really convinced, which I don't think they

01:15:02.960 --> 01:15:08.640
[Guest]: were, because, again, that method document was also opaque. I just don't get the motive that,

01:15:08.640 --> 01:15:13.760
[Guest]: you know, you're a statistical agency, all you do, like all statistical agencies in all countries is

01:15:13.760 --> 01:15:18.320
[Guest]: you follow a method, you try to improve, you come up with a number, it's a statistical process.

01:15:18.320 --> 01:15:25.680
[Guest]: But what's this obsession with defending a number, instead of just saying, this is what it is,

01:15:25.680 --> 01:15:28.240
[Guest]: this is a method, this is the data, figure it out for yourself.

01:15:28.240 --> 01:15:31.520
[Amit Varma]: So I'll ask a very, I mean, forgive me if this is too much of a newbie question.

01:15:31.520 --> 01:15:36.960
[Amit Varma]: I get why the state needs to know what the GDP is, because it's doing whatever economic planning it

01:15:36.960 --> 01:15:40.080
[Amit Varma]: is doing, though there could be an argument, it should do much less of it and just do the

01:15:40.080 --> 01:15:45.680
[Amit Varma]: basic things that it's supposed to do, like maintain the rule of law. And I get why political

01:15:45.680 --> 01:15:50.640
[Amit Varma]: parties need to know the GDP, because they want to make it part of their campaigns and the government

01:15:50.640 --> 01:15:54.400
[Amit Varma]: needs it for the optics of we are doing such a good job, the opposition needs it for the opposite

01:15:54.400 --> 01:16:00.240
[Amit Varma]: reason. But why do you and I, why do people in the actual regular participants in the actual

01:16:00.240 --> 01:16:03.440
[Amit Varma]: regular economy need to know what the GDP is? Why is it important?

01:16:03.440 --> 01:16:08.960
[Guest]: So the answer to that question is we don't need to know. You know, I mean, your life or my life,

01:16:08.960 --> 01:16:13.440
[Guest]: we won't be any worse off and nothing will be taken away from our life if we don't know how

01:16:13.440 --> 01:16:17.360
[Guest]: Indian GDP growth is doing. I mean, if I come to think of it before the internet age,

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:22.160
[Guest]: did people really know about how India is doing and what's the growth rate? No. I mean, because

01:16:22.160 --> 01:16:26.880
[Guest]: I think because of the internet age, because communication has become such a commodity today,

01:16:26.880 --> 01:16:31.520
[Guest]: that everybody starts taking interest in this one number in this GDP growth without even thinking

01:16:31.520 --> 01:16:36.720
[Guest]: why do we need to bother about it? I mean, it's another thing that newspapers are or media or

01:16:36.720 --> 01:16:40.880
[Guest]: whatever, they discuss it, because they want to question the government, which is perfectly fine

01:16:40.880 --> 01:16:46.160
[Guest]: in good faith. But is it really necessary to take the debate to this extent and make such a big deal

01:16:46.160 --> 01:16:50.400
[Guest]: of it? I don't think so. I think if there are economists or statisticians who know what they're

01:16:50.400 --> 01:16:54.160
[Guest]: talking about, and they are questioning the statistical agency, it should just remain between

01:16:54.160 --> 01:16:59.520
[Guest]: them. And end of the day, we should not give so much importance to GDP. I think what has happened

01:16:59.520 --> 01:17:05.280
[Guest]: over the last five years is we have given excessive importance to a number which is produced

01:17:05.280 --> 01:17:11.680
[Guest]: in a weak state capacity environment, and attempt to be consistent with international guidelines.

01:17:11.680 --> 01:17:18.080
[Guest]: But we have just given it this holy grail notion, or in other words, we have basically made a cult

01:17:18.080 --> 01:17:23.280
[Guest]: out of GDP. And therefore, the entire debate policy discussion just rotates around that number.

01:17:23.280 --> 01:17:27.520
[Guest]: It really doesn't have to be that exactly as you said, your life, my life doesn't change at all,

01:17:27.520 --> 01:17:31.760
[Guest]: if you don't know how the country is doing, and it's perfectly fine. But I think the debate should

01:17:31.760 --> 01:17:36.880
[Guest]: remain within the people who know what they're talking about, and should not become this popular

01:17:36.880 --> 01:17:42.960
[Guest]: debate. Because it is really a very complicated concept. And I would much rather it stays so,

01:17:42.960 --> 01:17:48.960
[Guest]: because otherwise, we end up assigning too much importance to an obscure, artificial number. And

01:17:48.960 --> 01:17:53.520
[Guest]: then you just lose the narrative, because then the focus is not on fixing the problems,

01:17:53.520 --> 01:17:58.240
[Guest]: the focus is defending, saying no, no, no, everything is fine. The focus all throughout

01:17:58.240 --> 01:18:02.640
[Guest]: the last four years should have been either acknowledging that there are some issues,

01:18:02.640 --> 01:18:06.640
[Guest]: fixing the problems, and all that the public gets to know is, yeah, the number has changed,

01:18:06.640 --> 01:18:08.560
[Guest]: and some other number has come out. So what big deal.

01:18:09.520 --> 01:18:12.880
[Amit Varma]: On the one hand, as we discussed earlier, it's a very nebulous number, like another

01:18:12.880 --> 01:18:17.040
[Amit Varma]: measure of that, which I was hearing about recently is that, you know, the states all

01:18:17.040 --> 01:18:21.600
[Amit Varma]: measure their own GDP as well. And when you put them all together, it doesn't add up to what the

01:18:21.600 --> 01:18:26.320
[Amit Varma]: India GDP is. Or if you measure the India GDP, you know, through a different approach, you said

01:18:26.320 --> 01:18:31.520
[Amit Varma]: there are three approaches, production, expenditure, so on, even those don't add up to each other. So

01:18:31.520 --> 01:18:36.480
[Amit Varma]: it's a very nebulous number. And we need to recognize that. But also the counter view to

01:18:36.480 --> 01:18:41.680
[Amit Varma]: that which strikes me is that in a democracy, especially a democracy, which you could argue

01:18:41.680 --> 01:18:47.360
[Amit Varma]: is going through turbulent times as ours might be, in a democracy, you need to hold you need to speak

01:18:47.360 --> 01:18:52.720
[Amit Varma]: truth to power, and you need to hold it accountable. And you need a metric for that to judge

01:18:52.720 --> 01:18:58.720
[Amit Varma]: how it is performing. For example, you know, it is plain common sense. And we see it all around

01:18:58.720 --> 01:19:04.880
[Amit Varma]: us that demonetization was an absolute disaster. But if they are throwing a GDP number at us,

01:19:04.880 --> 01:19:10.000
[Amit Varma]: which doesn't really indicate that you need a way to fight that and argue that and which is why

01:19:10.960 --> 01:19:15.120
[Amit Varma]: the counter view to this whole thing of you know, that GDP should not be a political issue

01:19:15.920 --> 01:19:20.640
[Amit Varma]: would be that because it is the metric out there of our government is performing in an economic

01:19:20.640 --> 01:19:25.040
[Guest]: context, it has to be a political issue. So the two ways to address what you're saying,

01:19:25.040 --> 01:19:29.760
[Guest]: and I completely agree with what you're saying to see, it's like, think of an example where if

01:19:29.760 --> 01:19:36.240
[Guest]: you tell students in a school or university that all that matters is your rank in class and your

01:19:36.240 --> 01:19:41.600
[Guest]: grades, and nothing else, then the students will try by hook or by crook by cheating by gaming,

01:19:41.600 --> 01:19:46.000
[Guest]: whatever it is, to get the high rank and to get get up the grades, which is exactly what countries

01:19:46.000 --> 01:19:49.840
[Guest]: are doing today. I mean, countries like ours or other countries that all that matters is the

01:19:49.840 --> 01:19:54.640
[Guest]: number and the growth rate and we will try to do whatever it takes. We'll game the system and get

01:19:54.640 --> 01:19:58.480
[Guest]: the growth rate up. There is a saying that if you can measure something, you can control it.

01:19:59.120 --> 01:20:02.480
[Guest]: So that's exactly what governments and it's not just our government, whatever, not government,

01:20:02.480 --> 01:20:07.120
[Guest]: but our country. It is happening in Greece, in Argentina, many, many other countries.

01:20:07.120 --> 01:20:12.000
[Guest]: But the thing is, if you want to hold the government or the system accountable on the

01:20:12.000 --> 01:20:17.200
[Guest]: basis of one number, that majority of the people don't even understand, then I think it's a very

01:20:17.200 --> 01:20:22.080
[Guest]: problematic scenario. I would much rather say that, and especially when it doesn't affect your

01:20:22.080 --> 01:20:25.840
[Guest]: day to day life. I mean, look at it this way, demonetization happened. Did anything show in

01:20:25.840 --> 01:20:30.080
[Guest]: the GDP? No. Is it just a function of flawed methodology or is it the case that really

01:20:30.080 --> 01:20:35.840
[Guest]: nothing happened? We don't know. So that metric itself is not a perfect measure of what you want

01:20:35.840 --> 01:20:41.920
[Guest]: to measure. And in a flawed metric, which is complicated and all of that, would you want to

01:20:41.920 --> 01:20:47.360
[Guest]: use that to hold the government accountable? As opposed to, let's say, for example, is jobs a

01:20:47.360 --> 01:20:52.240
[Guest]: better metric? Because jobs is something that does affect you and I. Today you and I would care about

01:20:52.240 --> 01:20:56.240
[Guest]: the fact, do we have a job? Do we have an income? That's something that immediately affects us.

01:20:56.240 --> 01:21:00.080
[Guest]: I would much rather be in a situation where I can hold the government accountable for the jobs,

01:21:00.080 --> 01:21:03.920
[Guest]: or not just the government, even the markets, whoever it is, right? That if the unemployment

01:21:03.920 --> 01:21:10.080
[Guest]: rate, or I call the non-employment rate, because non-employment also measures people who are not

01:21:10.080 --> 01:21:15.760
[Guest]: even looking for jobs. The situation has become so desperate that you're not even out there searching

01:21:15.760 --> 01:21:20.800
[Guest]: for a job. So I would much rather that that kind of a measure, that kind of a metric for an emerging

01:21:20.800 --> 01:21:27.040
[Guest]: country like India, is perhaps much more important. And it's relatively harder to fudge because people

01:21:27.040 --> 01:21:31.600
[Guest]: in their day-to-day lives can observe whether they have jobs or not. And we do an extremely

01:21:31.600 --> 01:21:36.320
[Guest]: poor measure of unemployment rate. I think there should have been a lot more discussion about

01:21:36.320 --> 01:21:41.360
[Guest]: improving unemployment or non-employment measures, as opposed to improving GDP measures,

01:21:41.360 --> 01:21:46.160
[Guest]: because it's a very, very abstract notion as opposed to jobs. But you'll see there's not much

01:21:46.160 --> 01:21:52.480
[Guest]: of a, other than the government withdrawing, not basically withholding that report, we don't see

01:21:52.480 --> 01:21:57.600
[Guest]: a lot of discussion in general about jobs and unemployment. It has become a recent fashion

01:21:57.600 --> 01:22:02.400
[Guest]: because of this withdrawal of the report and the Centre for Monitoring Indian Economy coming up

01:22:02.400 --> 01:22:07.760
[Guest]: with very high unemployment numbers. I think that needs a lot more focus. And if people really want

01:22:07.760 --> 01:22:12.080
[Guest]: to question something and really want to hold the government accountable for something, maybe that's

01:22:12.080 --> 01:22:18.480
[Guest]: that's it. Otherwise, I think if you pay too much emphasis on this one GDP number, it is very easy

01:22:18.480 --> 01:22:22.640
[Guest]: for the statistical agency to say, oh, we have done everything right. And what can you do after

01:22:22.640 --> 01:22:27.760
[Guest]: that? As I said, we are at an impasse. You know, it's been four years since the series came out.

01:22:27.760 --> 01:22:30.960
[Guest]: Have we achieved anything by holding the government accountable? Nothing. In fact,

01:22:30.960 --> 01:22:35.760
[Guest]: they are just doing more egregious things, like, as I said, releasing a back series and all of

01:22:35.760 --> 01:22:39.760
[Guest]: those things. Maybe we'll have another base year revision coming up, which can increase the growth

01:22:39.760 --> 01:22:44.880
[Guest]: rate even more. What can we really do? I mean, despite the noise that that has been created,

01:22:44.880 --> 01:22:48.960
[Guest]: the statistical agencies say, oh, we are perfect. We are following the international standards.

01:22:48.960 --> 01:22:54.000
[Guest]: This is the rate at which the economy is growing, as opposed to saying, let's get down to measuring

01:22:54.000 --> 01:22:57.920
[Guest]: unemployment or the job situation, because you look around and you see your friends don't have

01:22:57.920 --> 01:23:02.800
[Guest]: jobs. The salaries are not increasing commensurately with the growth or whatever inflation

01:23:02.800 --> 01:23:09.040
[Guest]: it is. That's something or not just jobs. Look at multiple things. Again, instead of holding the

01:23:09.040 --> 01:23:13.200
[Guest]: government accountable for one thing, you hold the government accountable for a few other things.

01:23:13.200 --> 01:23:17.920
[Guest]: If you want to talk about welfare, should India just measure its performance in terms of GDP

01:23:17.920 --> 01:23:22.560
[Guest]: growth? We may be the fastest growing country in the world, but we do so poorly in all the

01:23:22.560 --> 01:23:27.040
[Amit Varma]: other metrics of development, environment, climate change, etc. Like one of the alternative metrics,

01:23:27.040 --> 01:23:31.200
[Amit Varma]: which came up a couple of decades ago is the HDI, the Human Development Index, where again,

01:23:31.200 --> 01:23:34.560
[Amit Varma]: we don't do so well. And many economists have proposed that you don't look at the GDP,

01:23:34.560 --> 01:23:38.960
[Amit Varma]: you have a dashboard of metrics. And you know, you were speaking earlier of common sense metrics.

01:23:38.960 --> 01:23:44.960
[Amit Varma]: And I remember Donald Reagan's 1984 political campaign, where he basically asked the American

01:23:44.960 --> 01:23:49.120
[Amit Varma]: people to ask themselves one question, am I better off now than I was four years ago,

01:23:49.120 --> 01:23:52.880
[Amit Varma]: because he was fighting for re-election. And the thing is, if you ask the Indian voter for that,

01:23:52.880 --> 01:23:58.880
[Amit Varma]: that's a very nebulous question. Because number one, he may feel more at ease with a particular

01:23:58.880 --> 01:24:04.080
[Amit Varma]: sort of cultural narrative, even if he is not physically better off. Secondly, and this is

01:24:04.080 --> 01:24:08.320
[Amit Varma]: an objection which permeates through every single metric, what are the counterfactuals?

01:24:08.320 --> 01:24:12.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, if the labor laws were reformed, would he be much better off? That is just such a,

01:24:12.560 --> 01:24:15.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, I mean, how on earth do you measure something like that? You simply don't know the

01:24:15.600 --> 01:24:22.480
[Amit Varma]: counterfactuals. And that could really apply to, you know, any of all this. And therefore,

01:24:22.480 --> 01:24:26.240
[Amit Varma]: when it comes to something like the GDP, which is such a complicated number, like you put it,

01:24:26.240 --> 01:24:29.600
[Amit Varma]: essentially, I think what is going to happen is people are going to believe what they want to

01:24:29.600 --> 01:24:32.480
[Amit Varma]: believe, they're going to go with the narrative they want to believe, it's essentially going to

01:24:32.480 --> 01:24:37.360
[Amit Varma]: be tribal, where someone who supports the Prime Minister Modi will say, oh, the GDP is doing great

01:24:37.360 --> 01:24:41.920
[Amit Varma]: and the other side will say it's not. And it's ultimately a tribal decision and not a rational,

01:24:41.920 --> 01:24:46.640
[Amit Varma]: mathematical one. So my question to you now turning away from all of this, turning away from

01:24:46.640 --> 01:24:52.480
[Amit Varma]: the politicization of GDP and all of that, is that as an economist, and in your case, as an economist

01:24:52.480 --> 01:24:59.200
[Amit Varma]: who's written a lot on the GDP, and, you know, you are a sort of an expert on it, how do you now look

01:24:59.200 --> 01:25:05.840
[Amit Varma]: at where we are today? Like, if it's a completely useless metric, how do we move forward from here?

01:25:05.840 --> 01:25:10.080
[Amit Varma]: Is there any way past this? Or is it just basically, you know, given that the methodology is

01:25:10.080 --> 01:25:14.720
[Amit Varma]: now opaque, and given what the incentives are, is it just a completely nonsense figure, which you

01:25:14.720 --> 01:25:20.320
[Guest]: have to ignore as an economist? That's, that's exactly the question that I've been grappling

01:25:20.320 --> 01:25:26.160
[Guest]: with Amit for the last several, several months, if not a couple of years, is that as an economist,

01:25:26.160 --> 01:25:31.120
[Guest]: and especially as a macroeconomist, where my bread and butter, or my passion, so to speak,

01:25:31.120 --> 01:25:36.000
[Guest]: it depends a lot on using GDP as a statistic, because I'm an applied economist, is what do I

01:25:36.000 --> 01:25:41.200
[Guest]: do? What research do I do? Where do we go from here? And I have come to the conclusion myself

01:25:41.200 --> 01:25:48.240
[Guest]: that we cannot use the GDP number in our research, in our policy debates, in public discussions,

01:25:48.240 --> 01:25:53.440
[Guest]: because simply, A, B, or at least I, from whatever research I have done shows there are problems.

01:25:54.240 --> 01:25:57.760
[Guest]: And it's very difficult to trust that number unless the problems get fixed, or unless the

01:25:57.760 --> 01:26:02.960
[Guest]: statistical agency openly comes out about the caveats and qualifications. It is very hard. And

01:26:02.960 --> 01:26:07.920
[Guest]: where do we go from here? I would say, as you pointed out, dashboard of indicators that I think

01:26:07.920 --> 01:26:11.840
[Guest]: people are already looking at a bunch of indicators to get a sense of how the economy is doing.

01:26:11.840 --> 01:26:14.160
[Amit Varma]: The thing is, even those can be gamed eventually.

01:26:14.160 --> 01:26:17.520
[Guest]: Those can be gamed. But essentially, at that point, you just have to say that,

01:26:17.520 --> 01:26:21.920
[Guest]: you know, we are at a situation where we can't get a sense of how the economy is doing.

01:26:21.920 --> 01:26:26.080
[Guest]: I mean, the extreme pessimistic scenario, I would say, if you ask me how the Indian economy is

01:26:26.080 --> 01:26:30.720
[Guest]: doing, my answer would be as an economist, I don't know, because I have no way of measuring

01:26:30.720 --> 01:26:35.840
[Guest]: and assessing the performance. If I can't trust the national number, that's GDP. And if some of

01:26:35.840 --> 01:26:39.840
[Guest]: the indicators are also extremely volatile, because they fluctuate a lot. I have basically

01:26:39.840 --> 01:26:44.720
[Amit Varma]: no way of... And your point is that because the data which goes into all of this is so complicated,

01:26:44.720 --> 01:26:48.800
[Amit Varma]: it's really not possible for independent economists to sit down and come up with their

01:26:48.800 --> 01:26:53.680
[Guest]: own number. I mean, basically, a lot of attempts can be made using disaggregated information. So

01:26:53.680 --> 01:26:58.240
[Guest]: for example, if you collect household level data, or if you collect firm level data,

01:26:58.240 --> 01:27:03.600
[Guest]: you can assess sector wise performance. So you can get a sense of how the corporate India is

01:27:03.600 --> 01:27:08.720
[Guest]: performing, you can get a sense of how households are consuming, saving, etc. You can get a

01:27:08.720 --> 01:27:13.200
[Guest]: disaggregated picture. And then maybe you can just try to put things together in your mind and say,

01:27:13.200 --> 01:27:18.720
[Guest]: okay, this is roughly what the economy is doing. But it's very, very difficult to get a comprehensive

01:27:18.720 --> 01:27:23.680
[Guest]: view saying, oh, is economy is in a, what we call technically a recession, or an expansion meaning

01:27:23.680 --> 01:27:28.800
[Guest]: is it is it slowing down? Or is it accelerating? It's just very hard to say at this point of time.

01:27:28.800 --> 01:27:34.400
[Guest]: So I would say going forward, it's, it's a dark phase for, especially macroeconomists, you have

01:27:34.400 --> 01:27:40.080
[Guest]: to basically bank on non GDP, non performance related stuff. And you can't say anything about

01:27:40.080 --> 01:27:44.240
[Amit Varma]: the performance of the country. Can't. That's horrendously sad and depressing.

01:27:44.240 --> 01:27:49.200
[Amit Varma]: Let's, you know, before we end the episode, let's kind of take a step back out of India and go back

01:27:49.200 --> 01:27:54.640
[Amit Varma]: to the overall concept of the GDP per se. And again, it seems to me that just as a measure of

01:27:54.640 --> 01:28:00.240
[Amit Varma]: progress is very inadequate. You know, there's the example of the 1836, the world's richest guy dies

01:28:00.240 --> 01:28:04.800
[Amit Varma]: because he doesn't have an antibiotic. Just looking at my own life, you know, like when I was

01:28:04.800 --> 01:28:11.520
[Amit Varma]: growing up in the 80s and early 90s, you know, we had so little access to music, I remember how much

01:28:11.520 --> 01:28:16.080
[Amit Varma]: I would feel enriched if I managed to get together a mixtape from somewhere of music that was

01:28:16.080 --> 01:28:21.200
[Amit Varma]: otherwise not available in India. And today we can go to Amazon Prime or Google Play or Spotify and

01:28:21.200 --> 01:28:26.320
[Amit Varma]: press play and everything in the world is available to us. And we are hardly paying anything for it.

01:28:26.320 --> 01:28:31.520
[Amit Varma]: And the value that has been added to my life by technology in the last 20 years cannot possibly

01:28:31.520 --> 01:28:37.440
[Amit Varma]: be calculated. And none of it is because of the bloody status despite the state. You know, so

01:28:38.800 --> 01:28:42.880
[Guest]: if I can interrupt there. So one question, and again, I don't know the right answer to this,

01:28:42.880 --> 01:28:48.080
[Guest]: but it's something that I am questioning myself that how much do we really need to measure these

01:28:48.080 --> 01:28:53.280
[Guest]: things? Exactly. I mean, in the sense, yeah, there are many intrinsic implicit improvements happening

01:28:53.280 --> 01:28:58.160
[Guest]: in my life because of the day and age, because of access to better quality products and better

01:28:58.160 --> 01:29:04.800
[Guest]: quality services. But do we really need to measure all of these in an aggregative number? Or do we

01:29:04.800 --> 01:29:09.200
[Guest]: not? I mean, are we just are we just satisfied with saying, okay, there is this part of the economy

01:29:09.200 --> 01:29:14.160
[Guest]: that we can measure goods and services, physical, whatever it is, and we just start satisfied with

01:29:14.160 --> 01:29:18.320
[Guest]: that number, because it gives some idea of where the economy is going. You know, there's a saying

01:29:18.320 --> 01:29:24.160
[Guest]: that it is very hard to feed the soul when your stomach is empty. So there is some value in having

01:29:24.160 --> 01:29:30.000
[Guest]: that physical or whatever this GDP notion as well, if properly measured to show how the economy is

01:29:30.000 --> 01:29:34.160
[Guest]: performing over time. And yeah, there are shortcomings environmental where all of these

01:29:34.160 --> 01:29:38.880
[Guest]: things that that we have discussed, but maybe you come up with other measures, you know, there is a

01:29:38.880 --> 01:29:43.520
[Guest]: Human Development Index, where you can at least measure some life expectancy or literacy rate,

01:29:43.520 --> 01:29:48.080
[Guest]: or you figure out which cities are worth living in, you know, all of these rankings that come up

01:29:48.080 --> 01:29:53.200
[Guest]: with multiple, multiple things with their own flaws, etc. But do you really need a comprehensive

01:29:53.200 --> 01:29:57.520
[Guest]: measure of quality of life? Is it really necessary? I'm not so sure at this point of time, it's just

01:29:57.520 --> 01:30:01.840
[Guest]: that it's so difficult to measure. And something which is difficult to measure, do you really want

01:30:01.840 --> 01:30:07.760
[Guest]: to put resources of a state which is already struggling with weak state capacity? Do you

01:30:07.760 --> 01:30:13.040
[Guest]: really want to put the resources to do something like that? I'm not so sure. Or is it that the case

01:30:13.040 --> 01:30:17.920
[Guest]: that countries like the US, Australia, Canada, which have already achieved a very high per capita

01:30:17.920 --> 01:30:22.640
[Guest]: level of income, they should stop worrying about GDP growth, because they've already achieved that

01:30:22.640 --> 01:30:28.960
[Guest]: level. And they have the luxury of now coming up with all of these other things. And at some point

01:30:28.960 --> 01:30:34.080
[Guest]: of time, when we have crossed all our major obstacles, then maybe we can figure out whether

01:30:34.080 --> 01:30:38.000
[Guest]: we can do that or not. Again, these are just questions, I don't have the right answers. But

01:30:38.000 --> 01:30:44.080
[Guest]: it's worth also asking ourselves, how much I'm all for economic measurement. But how much do you

01:30:44.080 --> 01:30:49.120
[Guest]: really want to measure, knowing that all the measurements will be perfect? These are very wise

01:30:49.120 --> 01:30:53.840
[Amit Varma]: words. So basically, what you're saying, correct me if I'm wrong, is that the GDP is a very flawed

01:30:53.840 --> 01:30:58.960
[Amit Varma]: measure. And while we can tweak it and do this and that, there's really no need to look for a

01:30:58.960 --> 01:31:03.280
[Amit Varma]: better measure than that. Because why measure all of these things, just go to Google Play,

01:31:03.280 --> 01:31:06.480
[Amit Varma]: press play, enjoy the music, right? That's absolutely the thing. I shouldn't have said

01:31:06.480 --> 01:31:10.640
[Amit Varma]: that because I don't even sponsor it. And it's like a random plug that I'm giving, go to Amazon

01:31:10.640 --> 01:31:15.280
[Guest]: Prime. Yeah, sometimes I think we should just, you know, as I said, relax a little bit, not

01:31:15.280 --> 01:31:20.000
[Guest]: overthink, not overthink it. As I said, I keep saying the same thing. You have weak state capacity

01:31:20.000 --> 01:31:23.520
[Guest]: do not attach so much importance to a number that is coming out of the state agencies.

01:31:24.080 --> 01:31:28.080
[Guest]: It is what it is. Yeah, there are debates that economists and statisticians will do it.

01:31:28.080 --> 01:31:32.240
[Guest]: But do the common public really need to get so involved in it when they don't even understand

01:31:32.240 --> 01:31:36.800
[Guest]: what it is and it doesn't affect their daily life? Perhaps not. So I think if the debate

01:31:36.800 --> 01:31:44.480
[Guest]: gets a little bit more confined and the emphasis is put on fixing things and improving things

01:31:44.480 --> 01:31:49.840
[Guest]: and moving on, it will probably be better rather than sensationalizing it. And as far as alternative

01:31:49.840 --> 01:31:54.000
[Guest]: measures are concerned, I think this debate is going to be continuing because it's coming up

01:31:54.000 --> 01:31:57.440
[Guest]: from the developed countries and anything that starts in the developed countries will continue

01:31:57.440 --> 01:32:03.360
[Guest]: for a very long time. So I think till they figure out in their peace of mind, what are the alternative

01:32:03.360 --> 01:32:08.000
[Guest]: measures or what are the supplementary measures? It's too premature for us to get into that debate

